    <div class="section-num">09 — FAQ</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Bertazzoni Repair FAQ</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">How much does Bertazzoni appliance repair cost in Los Angeles?</div><div class="faq-a">Most Bertazzoni repairs run $89–$560. Oven calibration (no parts) is on the low end. Igniter or temperature sensor replacement is $175–$320. Control board or induction inverter runs higher. Diagnostic fee is $89, waived on repair. Written flat-rate estimate before work begins.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Do you service Heritage series color-panel Bertazzoni appliances?</div><div class="faq-a">Yes — and we take color panel protection seriously. Heritage Arancio, Rosso, Giallo, Verde, Blu, and all other colors get felt-backed tools and full-panel protective covers throughout service. The colored enamel is the point of the appliance — we won't leave scratch marks. This is a specific part of our Heritage service protocol, not an afterthought.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">My Bertazzoni oven runs hot — does that mean the sensor needs replacement?</div><div class="faq-a">Not necessarily. Many Bertazzoni oven temperature issues are calibration offsets, not sensor failures. We test with a calibrated probe at multiple setpoints before ordering any parts. Bertazzoni allows ±35°F software calibration through the service menu — a calibration adjustment costs a fraction of a sensor replacement. We always check calibration first.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Do you service all four Bertazzoni design series?</div><div class="faq-a">Yes — Master, Heritage, Professional, and Modern all share the same core technical platform. The differences between series are aesthetic: panel designs, handle styles, color options. We service all four identically from a technical standpoint, with additional color-panel protocols for Heritage models.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">My Bertazzoni induction cooktop has a dead zone — does it need a new cooktop?</div><div class="faq-a">Almost certainly not. Single-zone failures on Bertazzoni induction cooktops are almost always inverter board failures, not glass surface damage. E3 and similar fault codes specifically indicate inverter faults. We test inverter current for each zone independently. Board replacement is a fraction of full cooktop cost — correct diagnosis here saves hundreds of dollars.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Where is Bertazzoni made?</div><div class="faq-a">Bertazzoni is made in Guastalla, Emilia-Romagna, Italy — the same region as Ferrari and Lamborghini. The company has been family-owned for five generations since 1882 and continues to manufacture in Italy. This heritage is reflected in the build quality that makes these appliances worth repairing rather than replacing.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Do you repair Bertazzoni dual-fuel ranges?</div><div class="faq-a">Yes. Bertazzoni dual-fuel ranges have a gas cooktop and an electric oven — two independent systems. Gas side: sealed burner igniter diagnosis and service. Electric side: bake element, convection fan, and control board. When a dual-fuel shows multiple symptoms, we determine whether they share a cause before ordering anything.</div></div>
    </div>
